article.description:
Shannon Johnson scored 15 points and had a
dozen assists Friday night, leading the San Antonio Silver Stars to
a 72-63 win over the Sacramento Monarchs.
article.headline: Johnson's double-double does it for Stars
article.linkText: San Antonio starts slow but overcomes Sacramento
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Shannon Johnson showed Friday night why
she'll be playing point guard in the Olympics.

Johnson had 15 points and matched her career high with a dozen
assists while leading the San Antonio Silver Stars to a 72-63 win
over the Sacramento Monarchs.

The win was San Antonio's third in four games this season.

"This is a very confident team," said Johnson, who was among
the first players selected for the U.S. team that will play in
Athens. "I was happy that my teammates stayed behind me. They kept
pushing me."

The Silver Stars fell behind 8-0 before Johnson made a 17-footer
to start a 17-8 run that gave them the lead for good midway through
the first half. San Antonio built its lead to 17 points late in the
game.

Adrienne Goodson led the Silver Stars with 17 points on 7-for-12
shooting, while Marie Ferdinand had 16 and LaToya Thomas 12. Margo
Dydek paced all rebounders with 10.

"It was definitely a struggle trying to find my shot," said
Goodson, who came into the game shooting only 3-for-23 from the
floor.

Yolanda Griffith led Sacramento with 19 points, nine rebounds
and six steals. DeMya Walker added 11 points for the Monarchs.

"We weren't that aggressive and it showed," said Walker.
"Other teams are going to bring their `A' game, and we need to
come out and bring our `A' game."

Sacramento made four of its first six shots, while San Antonio
went scoreless until Johnson's first basket nearly four minutes
into the game.

The Silver Stars went ahead 17-16 on a layup by Goodson, and
they pulled out as far as eight points just before the break.

San Antonio tightened its inside defense in the second half,
while also improving its shooting. The Silver Stars went 11-for-20
in the final 20 minutes, and outscored the Monarchs at the free
throw line 22-9.

Monarchs coach John Whisenant pointed at his team's subpar
defense as the key to a second loss in three games this season.

"We feel like we're the type of team who dominates defensively
and can be a top-flight team, and we didn't do that tonight," he
said.

Sacramento, forced to shoot more outside shots, went 13-for-36
(36 percent) in the second half. The Monarchs were 4-for-17 on
3-pointers.
